<p style="text-align:justify;">The Indians of the Missisouri and particularly the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Gros Ventres</span> Sell you a thing<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> take payment go away seemingly satisfied &#8212; but upon reflection they will regret the bargain and return when they often insist upon undoing what they had done by taking their own back and returning yours unless you Choose to bear the imposition of paying double which is the intention<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Of this I can speak from experience.  I procured an Excellent Horse for which I paid one hundred and twent<span class="AddHand-author">y</span> five beaver skins in goods equal to Fifty pounds Stl<sup>g</sup> within an hour after the Indian who sold him brought the things back and took away the horse and was impertinent to the bargain<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Another Indian sold me the Tail of a Turkey cock for a fan<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I paid him his price he went off but soon returned and doubled his demand to which I agreed he returned again and again and I was at last under the</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">necessity</p>

